# Intervention and Control of Network Management Agent (ICON)

This document provides a short description of a proposed IETF work.
The intention of this document is to capture the scope of a piece of work that the proponents believes is in IETF scope and needs urgent attention.
Our hope is that Area Directors will help us dispatch this to a place to do the work:
- an existing working group
- a new working group

The proponents fully intend to continue refining existing Internet-Drafts concurrent with any work-dispatch process.

Some explanation of terminology is provided after the problem statement that uses some of the terms.

## Problem Statement and Work Scope

Network operations are increasingly autonomous with the growth of network management Agent applications at the network level and
service level. Since AI native operations are non-deterministic, when network management agents misbehave or deviate from what
Agents are expected to do, AI Guardrails such as input guardrail, output guardrail are introduced to constrain the behavior of
AI agents within operational and ethical boundaries, prevent AI from producing harmful results, e.g.,escalate a decision to a
human for high-risk network operation,in the meanwhile protect against malicious attacks,e.g., prompt injection.

However the pace of AI Agent technology adoption is exceeding network operators' abilities to assure and control them. Network
operators usually lack equivalent infrastructure for human oversight that match the speed and scale of the network management
Agent applications,e.g.,network failure or security risk is hard to detect and control, occurring at machine speed.

The goal of this work is to explore use cases, derive requirements, and provide solutions for continuous monitoring and evaluation,
identifying and characterizing trajectory records related to agent behavior or workflow operation, enable human oversight, provide
human and agent interaction for agent intervention and control at the service level and network level.

Where possible, any solutions work will be built in a modular way using existing IETF protocols. However, no protocol solution
choices will be made until the requirements (functional and behavioral) have been agreed, and then this will require an analysis
of the capabilities of existing protocols and what gaps need to be filled.

